name: 3,4,4-trimethyl-2-pentanol
source: Wilhoit R. C. Physical and Thermodynamic Properties of Aliphatic Alcohols. (Supplement to Journal of Physical and Chemical Reference Data; Vol 2; No. 1.); American Chemical Society; Washington; 1973.
Reason: Starting with the base structure of pentane which has a melting point of -129.7°C, we need to consider the effects of adding functional groups. The addition of three methyl groups theoretically increases the melting point due to increased molecular weight and branching which raises the melting point because it makes the molecule more compact and reduces surface area, alleviating some of the Van der Waals forces. Each methyl group typically increases the melting point by approximately 20°C, giving us a 60°C increase. However, the introduction of a hydroxyl group (alcohol) induces the capability for hydrogen bonding, which also significantly increases the melting point. The effect of a hydroxyl group can raise the melting point by about 50°C to 70°C when comparing simple alkanes to their alcohol counterparts. Taking an average effect of 60°C for the hydroxyl group, we have a total predicted increase of 120°C. When we apply these adjustments to the base melting point of pentane, this results in a value of: -129.7 + 60 + 60 = -9.7°C. However, this is only an estimated approach and actual experimental values also depend on the particular structural conformation and other specific intermolecular forces at play in the compound. Note that due to the size and branching of the molecule, the actual increase in melting point due to methyl groups may be less than the estimated 20°C each, so the predicted value might be an overestimation and should be adjusted downward.

name: 3,4,4-trimethyl-2-pentanol
source: Wilhoit R. C. Physical and Thermodynamic Properties of Aliphatic Alcohols. (Supplement to Journal of Physical and Chemical Reference Data; Vol 2; No. 1.); American Chemical Society; Washington; 1973.
Reason: Starting from pentane with a melting point of -129.7°C, the introduction of three methyl groups increases molecular weight and branching, typically raising the melting point. The increase due to methyl groups is less pronounced in high molecular weight compounds, so we can assume an increase of about 10°C per methyl group, resulting in a total increase of 30°C. The hydroxyl group introduces hydrogen bonding, significantly raising the melting point. The increase can be approximated as 20°C for a single hydroxyl group in such a molecule, due to steric hindrance from the bulky t-butyl group which may limit hydrogen bonding efficiency. Adding the increases together gives -129.7°C + 30°C (from methyl groups) + 20°C (from the hydroxyl group) = -79.7°C. This is significantly lower than the actual value of 27.0°C. To reconcile this, we need to consider that branching near the hydroxyl group can further raise the melting point as it creates a more compact structure that is difficult to pack in the solid state, leading to an increase in the melting point. Adjusting the prediction to account for these effects should bring it closer to the actual value reported.
